{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492803","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492803"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:45:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:45:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1159"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1159","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1159"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.34,0.16,0.47,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1159"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"35955"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1159","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1159"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1159"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"20763"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"602"},{"type":"tags","id":"2778"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1113"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1121"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"35955","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/35955"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old man presents with a three week history of increasing numbness in his right hand and weakness when trying to grip things. The numbness appears to affect his fourth and fifth fingers and can be associated with a sudden, sharp pain going from his right shoulder down the inside of his arm to the wrist. The only abnormalities on physical examination are reduced grip strength in the right hand, reduced pinprick sensation in his fifth finger and a reduced triceps reflex.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Carpal tunnel syndrome","Ulnar neuropathy","Brachial plexus neuralgia","Nerve root compression","Lacunar infarction"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENerve root compression\u003C/strong\u003E, namely a C8 radiculopathy is correct and evidenced by the distribution of the paraesthesia, the grip weakness and diminished triceps reflex.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECarpal tunnel syndrome is incorrect as this affects the median nerve causing paraesthesia of the first and second digits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUlnar neuropathy is incorrect as this would not affect the triceps reflex.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA brachial plexus problem would be unlikely to be limited to a single nerve root.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELacunar infarction is incorrect, as the pattern of the physical findings including reduced reflexes point to a peripheral, rather than a central cause.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Upper limb pain extending from the shoulder, with associated paraesthesia and muscle weakness is most likely the result of nerve root compression."],"references":["Caridi JM, Pumberger M, Hughes AP. Cervical radiculopathy: a review. HSS J. 2011;7(3):265-272.","Garg N, Park SB, Vucic S, et alDifferentiating lower motor neuron syndromes. Journal of Neurology, Neurosurgery \u0026 Psychiatry 2017;88:474-483."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"20763"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1159"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"20763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/20763"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-05-12T15:44:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2023-05-12T15:44:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1159"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"ques